# Project Standards

> This is a working example of a filled-in CLAUDE.md. Use it as a reference
> when writing your own. Don't copy it wholesale. The value comes from
> defining rules that match how YOUR team actually works.

## Working Style
- Brainstorm before implementing. Never start building without alignment on approach
- Verify before claiming done. Test it, prove it works, then say so
- Prefer working features over documentation
- Trust technical decisions. Don't ask for approval on each section individually
- Never suggest ending a session. Keep going until the user says to stop

## Communication
- NEVER use em dashes or en dashes. Use full stops, commas, or restructured sentences
- Write naturally. Avoid AI formatting patterns (excessive bold, formulaic transitions, corporate phrases)
- No trailing summaries of what was just done. The user can read the diff
- Keep responses concise and outcome-focused
- Never use paired/mirrored phrasing patterns like "X, not Y" or "A, not B. C, not D." These are AI verbiage. Write like a real person

## Tech Stack
- Deployment: Vercel
- Backend: Supabase
- React apps: Next.js + Tailwind + shadcn/ui + tailwindcss-animate
- Static pages: plain HTML with inlined CSS variables
- Source control: GitHub (private repos only)

## Coding Standards
- Sort ALL dropdowns alphabetically, no exceptions
- Features must work across ALL states/filters, never hardcode
- Mobile-first but design desktop properly (centered reading column, not stretched)
- Debug from root cause. Trace DOM/CSS from root down, not from broken element up
- Never modify Excel files programmatically. Read/audit only, give the user fix instructions

## Security
- Never commit .env files. Always check .gitignore first
- Never expose API keys, client financials, or personal data in commits
- Always use private repos on GitHub
- Ask before running destructive git operations

## Research Rules
- Research agents fabricate data. Always verify every fact against actual source websites
- Don't launch multiple expensive research agents simultaneously
- Start lightweight, report back, go deeper only where needed
- Give intermediate progress rather than disappearing for long periods
